    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA115-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu piriviṭai āṟṟāḷāya talaimakaḷai tōḻi paruvaṅ koṇṭāṭi (ER, ET: kāṭṭi) vaṟpuṟuttiyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante comforts HER, who was unable to bear it during the separation, by appreciating the season.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA115">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            malarnta poykaip pūkkuṟ ṟaḻuṅka</l>
<l>            vayarnta vāyaṅ kaṇṇiṉitu paṭīiya</l>
<l>            raṉṉaiyuñ ciṟitutaṇin tuyiriṉa ḷiṉṉīrt</l>
<l>            taṭaṅkal vāyilu muṇṭuci ṉīreṉa</l>
<l>            mayilaṭi yilaiya mākkura ṉocci </l>
<l>            maṉainaṭu mauvalō ṭūḻmukai yaviḻak</l>
<l>            kāretirn taṉṟāṟ kālai kātalar</l>
<l>            tavaccēy nāṭṭā rāyiṉu mikappē</l>
<l>            raṉpiṉar vāḻi tōḻi naṉpuka</l>
<l>            ḻulappiṉṟu peṟiṉun taviralar </l>
<l>            kēṭṭici ṉallaṉō vicumpiṉ ṟakavē.</l>
    </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent">“While the eyes of [my] companions, who were engaged to the point of</l>
<l rend="indent">exhaustion in plucking flowers in the pond that bloomed, close pleasantly,</l>
<l rend="indent">mother is one who sighs, a little appeased, and in the opening</l>
<l rend="indent">of broad stones with sweet water there is some water”,</l>
<l rend="indent4">[with these thoughts]<note place="foot">The exact construction and impact of lines 1-4 are unclear; I take the double -<term xml:lang="ta">um</term> on <term xml:lang="ta">aṉṉai</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">vāyil</term> as a mark of to coordinate sentences and, accordingly, read <term xml:lang="ta">uṇṭu</term> as a finite verb. While the general idea of line 4 (however the syntax) seems to be that water at last has come, the relation of this to the mother and female attendants is a puzzle even to T.V.G. Perhaps we simply have to assume that the women are engaged in a kind of occupation only possible during the rains.</note></l>
<l>the rainy season has indeed come to face [us],</l>
<l rend="indent">for the mature buds on the big-eared Nocci tree with peacock-foot leaves</l>
<l rend="indent2">to open along with [those of] the wild jasmine in the house.</l>
<l rend="indent4">At [that] time<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kālai</term> is a little awkward in this way, but what else to do with it?</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent2">even if [my<note place="foot">Depending on which pronoun is inserted here – "me" or "you" – the poem is spoken by HER or by the confidante.</note>] lover is in a very distant land,</l>
<l>he has very great love, oh friend.</l>
<l rend="indent2">Even if today he were to procure the waste of good praise<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ulappu/uvappu</term>: apart from the fact that l and v look so similar in the mss., it seems plausible that ER chose the <term xml:lang="ta">uvappu</term> ("joy") variant with the G mss., without however following their other deviations. The message seems to be in any case that even at a risk to the success of his undertakings, HE will think of his promise to HER and be on his way.</note>,</l>
<l>he won't be restrained.</l>
<l rend="indent3">Don't I hear the 
    <choice>
    <seg>sky call today?</seg>
    <seg>readiness of the sky?</seg>
    </choice></l>
        </lg>
